==================================================
REQUIRED TEST SCENARIOS
==================================================

The automated harness must validate these core scenarios wherever practical:

Scenario 1 — Basic Multi-Event Recording
- start recording
- click several elements
- ensure more than one event is captured
- ensure UI updates live
- stop recording
- verify final JSON contains all events in order

Scenario 2 — Typing / Form Interaction
- start recording
- type into an input
- interact with a button or form
- ensure input-related events are captured as intended
- stop recording
- verify output integrity

Scenario 3 — Navigation Resilience
- start recording
- navigate to another page
- continue interacting
- verify recording remains active or reattaches correctly
- verify later events are not lost

Scenario 4 — Session Lifecycle
- start recording
- record several events
- stop recording
- start a new session
- verify the previous session does not pollute the next

Scenario 5 — Append-Only Event Storage
- send multiple events through the pipeline
- verify the session store appends instead of replaces

Scenario 6 — UI Sync
- verify the event list shown in the UI matches the canonical stored event stream

Scenario 7 — Export Validation
- verify exported/final JSON is valid, complete, ordered, and schema-compliant

==================================================
TEST QUALITY STANDARDS
==================================================

Your tests must be meaningful.

Avoid:
- trivial assertions that only check existence
- snapshot-only tests with no semantic validation
- tests that merely mirror implementation details
- brittle hacks that fail for irrelevant reasons
- fake success criteria

Prefer:
- behavioral assertions
- explicit validation of recorder outcomes
- stable fixtures
- readable test names
- maintainable helpers
- reusable test utilities
- clear failure messages

==================================================
TESTABILITY-DRIVEN REFACTORING
==================================================

If the current code is too tangled to test properly, improve the architecture carefully.

Examples of helpful refactors:
- extract event normalization into pure functions
- isolate message contract handlers
- isolate session store logic
- create a canonical recorder state module
- separate UI rendering from state mutation
- centralize event schema definitions
- add explicit interfaces around extension APIs

Refactor only as much as needed to create a strong test harness.

